<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: HOUSEHOLD TOXIC WASTE REPORT IS ORDERED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Los Angeles City Council panel Monday ordered city officials to return next 
week with a report on funding a program to collect household hazardous wastes 
from homeowners before the items end up in the regular trash. 
</P>
<P>
The council's Environmental Quality and Waste Management Committee also sided 
with residents who live near Lopez Canyon, the city-owned landfill in the 
northeast San Fernando Valley, in expressing unhappiness that the city's 
fledgling household hazardous waste pickup program has been stalled. 
</P>
<P>
The city has $957,000 in its budget for such a clean-up plan, but it will 
require a City Council vote to free the funds for expenditure. Presently, 
release of the funds depends on completion of a report on ways to handle the 
expensive job of collecting and disposing of such wastes. 
</P>
