<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GE Says PCBs Break Down Naturally: General Electric Co. released a report that 
it says shows the natural biodegradation of polychlorinated biphenyls in New 
York's Hudson River. 
</P>
<P>
The company had dumped PCBs in the river for about 25 years, when the practice 
was legal and before the substances were suspected of harming human health. 
Recently, the state has proposed dredging the river to remove the contaminated 
material to a landfill. GE said its results match those of a 1984 New York 
Department of Environmental Conservation report, but it couldn't say whether 
the natural process would rid the river of all PCBs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
